  "text": "Let Q be a finite quiver and W a potential. Let Γ(Q, W ) be the complete Ginzburg dg algebra associated with the quiver with potential (Q, W ), see [Gi, KeY] . The algebra H 0 Γ(Q, W ) is known as the Jacobian algebra, and if it is finite-dimensional, we say that (Q, W ) is Jacobi-finite. By definition Γ(Q, W ) is concentrated in non-positive degrees. According to [CITATION_1] Theorem A.17 (ii) 2 -ctilt(U (Q,W ) (b) Assume that Q is related to a Dynkin quiver Q ′ by a finite sequence of quiver mutations. Since W is a nondegenerate potential, the quiver of the mutated quiver with potential µ i (Q, W ) is just the mutated quiver µ i (Q) and the potential of µ i (Q, W ) is again nondenegerate. From the assumption, we have a finite sequence of mutations µ i 1 • · · · • µ i ℓ (Q) = Q ′ and hence we obtain µ i 1 • · · · • µ i ℓ (Q, W ) = (Q ′ , 0). Since KQ ′ = H 0 Γ(Q ′ , 0) is representation-finite, it follows from [CITATION_2] Corollary 4.6 ] that H 0 Γ(Q, W ) is representation-finite. As a consequence, H 0 Γ(Q, W ) is τ -tilting finite and by the first statement per( Γ(Q, W )) is silting-discrete.",
